1
00:00:00,450 --> 00:00:11,800
This video explains one finding in plain English. A
beach can look clean, then suddenly spike. The goal is
to rank which clean beaches deserve attention before
that surprise happens.

2
00:00:12,450 --> 00:00:24,800
The model improved in three steps. The unified onset
model scored zero point two nine nine two AP. Adding
physics pi raised it to zero point three three four
eight. Adding the strict causal tensor raised it again
to zero point three four one eight.

3
00:00:25,450 --> 00:00:37,100
Physics pi tells us why a spike might happen. Rain can
move bacteria toward the beach. Heat, sunlight, and
flushing can change whether bacteria grow, die, clear
out, or get trapped.

4
00:00:38,450 --> 00:00:50,800
The strict causal tensor tells us something different.
It reads public ocean, weather, station, seasonal,
regional, and water quality context, then asks whether
the whole coast is in an unusual state today.

5
00:00:51,450 --> 00:01:02,800
Together, the two ideas help the ranker. Physics
explains local causes. The tensor adds the wider coast
state. The result is a better list of clean beaches
that may suddenly become risky.

6
00:01:03,450 --> 00:01:15,800
For counties, this is triage. It is not an official
closure button. It is a way to decide which clean
beaches should be inspected or sampled first after
rain, heat, wind, flushing, or regional state changes.

7
00:01:16,450 --> 00:01:28,800
For new markets, physics pi can help early because
rain, sun, runoff, and flushing exist everywhere. The
tensor adds a smaller extra signal after enough public
cross-source context exists.

8
00:01:29,450 --> 00:01:41,800
That is the product difference. Many tools mostly use
station memory, rain rules, or local history. This
ranker also reads a broader coastal estate state
across weather, ocean, sources, and region.

9
00:01:42,450 --> 00:01:53,800
Bottom line: the physics says why a spike might
happen. The tensor says the coast is acting weird
today. Together they improve the early-warning ranker
for the event customers care about.
